WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.680
Fantastic work!

2
00:00:02.680 --> 00:00:06.960
You created a powerful tool to guide make versus buy analysis.

3
00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:06.960


4
00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:06.960


5
00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:11.400
In Chapter 1, we started by developing a quote analysis tool and learning

6
00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:16.640
how to calculate extended and full cost for the volumes provided in the quotes.

7
00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:16.640


8
00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:16.640


9
00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:21.000
In Chapter 2, we developed a dynamic scenario analysis tool to

10
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
calculate full costs over a wider range of potential production volumes.

11
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:25.000


12
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:25.840


13
00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:33.520
In Chapter 3, we added analysis of the make option by calculating full cost based on our internal estimates data.

14
00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:36.640
In the end, we had a really useful model.

15
00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:36.640


16
00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:36.640


17
00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:40.400
The model is a great baseline for more complex analysis.

18
00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:44.480
You can extend the model to include more cost considerations not covered in this case

19
00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:52.080
study, such as salaried employees, more facilities, variable overheads, and freight costs.

20
00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:52.080


21
00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:52.080


22
00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:56.360
You can also build in other vital supply chain aspects, such as time and quality.

23
00:00:56.360 --> 00:00:56.360


24
00:00:56.360 --> 00:00:57.080


25
00:00:57.080 --> 00:01:00.440
But it's time to address the elephant in the room.

26
00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:00.440


27
00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:00.440


28
00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:05.040
Historically this type of supply chain and financial analysis would occur in spreadsheets.

29
00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:06.680
Why are we using Power BI instead?

30
00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:06.680


31
00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:06.680


32
00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:13.400
Power BI offers some huge advantages for analyzing quotes as well as internal manufacturing cost data.

33
00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:13.400


34
00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:14.120


35
00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:18.160
Even if you understand why Power BI might be a superior tool for this type of analysis,

36
00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:22.600
this video contains some points that might convince your manager and the rest of your team as well.

37
00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:22.600


38
00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:23.560


39
00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:28.320
After you create a functional data model, you can add more quotes data, and the same logic will be applied.

40
00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:33.120
This means your analysis logic will be consistent across projects.

41
00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:36.400
In many cases, supply chain teams may instead create a new

42
00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:40.080
spreadsheet for every project or even every part of a project!

43
00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:40.080


44
00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:40.080


45
00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:44.360
Power BI also helps control source data.

46
00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:47.080
When quote data is entered and manipulated in spreadsheets,

47
00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:51.000
it can easily be changed by someone in the analysis process.

48
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.440
You don't want your analysis to be based on flawed data.

49
00:01:54.440 --> 00:01:59.400
In Power BI, an analyst rarely touches the raw data after it is loaded.

50
00:01:59.400 --> 00:01:59.400


51
00:01:59.400 --> 00:01:59.400


52
00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:03.760
Imagine the following scenario - you are presenting to several key decision-makers.

53
00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:03.760


54
00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:03.760


55
00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:08.440
You say, "The best option for Part XYZ is Supplier A".

56
00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:08.440


57
00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:08.440


58
00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:10.480
"For what volume?"

59
00:02:10.480 --> 00:02:12.160
one of the leaders interjects.

60
00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:12.160


61
00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:12.160


62
00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:14.240
"10,000 units", you reply.

63
00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:14.240


64
00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:14.240


65
00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:15.560
"Didn't you hear?

66
00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:18.080
The estimate is 30,000 units now!"

67
00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:19.280
the leader replies.

68
00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:19.280


69
00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:19.280


70
00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:24.560
If you have your analysis in spreadsheets, you would either have to close out your slide deck and

71
00:02:24.560 --> 00:02:29.600
open up the spreadsheet, or more likely, you say "We'll have to crunch the numbers and get back to you."

72
00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:29.600


73
00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:29.600


74
00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:33.880
Because you use Power BI, you simply say, "Thanks for the update.

75
00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:37.480
Let's see what happens to the analysis when you move the volume parameter."

76
00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:38.440


77
00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:38.440


78
00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:43.880
In moments like this, the investment in building a great data model with clear visuals really pays off.

79
00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:43.880


80
00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:43.880


81
00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:47.240
Congratulations on completing this case study!

82
00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:54.840
You have made a useful tool for your organization and improved your abilities as a supply chain analyst.

